YELLOW FEVER - AMERICAS (07): BRAZIL (SANTA CATARINA)
*****************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Tue 28 Apr 2020
Source: NSC [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
https://www.nsctotal.com.br/noticias/sobe-para-15-o-numero-de-pacientes-contaminados-por-febre-amarela-em-santa-catarina


Santa Catarina has 15 patients infected with yellow fever, according to information issued by the office of Epidemiological Surveillance this past Monday (27 Apr 2020).

There are 2 cases more in relation to the previous bulletin issued 15 days earlier. Of the total number of people who have contracted the disease, 6 were diagnosed in Blumenau, in the Vale of Itajai.

The number of deaths remains the same; 2 deaths in 2020, both registered in the month of March 2020. The 1st death is a man in Camboriu according to the state registry. The victim was 42 years of age and was hospitalized in Balneario Camboriu. The 2nd registered [death] occurred on 31 Mar [2020] and was a man 52 years of age in the municipality of Indaial. Neither of these victims were vaccinated against the disease.

Besides Blumenau, residents of 5 other municipalities have contracted the disease this year [2020]. In Pomerode and Indaial, 6 people have been registered with the infection, 3 in each city. Camboriu, Jaragua do Sul and Sao Bento Sul, no Norte of SC, had one case each.

According to the office of Epidemiological Surveillance, the disease is also circulating in other municipalities where dead monkeys infected by the virus have been reported. The primates hit with the disease were registered in other cities where there are still no human cases diagnosed: Gaspar, Timbo, Campo Alegre, Rio Negrinho, Luiz Alves and Doutor Pedrinho.

Yellow fever is a serious disease that is transmitted by mosquitoes in wildland areas and near forests. It is a disease that progresses rapidly. The infection results in the following symptoms:
- Fever with up to 7 days duration
- Intense headache
- Abdominal pain
- hemorrhagic manifestations
- Icterus
- Elevated transaminases

[Byline: Clarissa Battistella]

